## Checklist Enforcement

### Required Checklist Completion

All checklist items must be either:

- **Checked** `- [x]` if completed/applicable
- **Explained** if not applicable (add comment explaining why)

Note: ‚ÄúN/A + reason‚Äù is acceptable for checklist items but NOT as the sole content of a section.

‚ùå **Avoid**: Unchecked items without explanation

```markdown
- [ ] Code follows project style guidelines and naming conventions
- [ ] All new code has appropriate test coverage
```

‚úÖ **Good**: Properly addressed items

```markdown
- [x] Code follows project style guidelines and naming conventions
- [x] All new code has appropriate test coverage
- [x] Linter warnings and errors have been resolved
- [x] No debugging code or console logs remain
- [x] TypeScript strict mode compliance verified
- [ ] End-to-end tests updated ‚Äî N/A (documentation-only PR)
```

## Format Consistency Standards

### Markdown Structure

- Use consistent header levels (`###` for main sections)
- Maintain emoji prefixes for section headers
- Include horizontal rule before checklist: `---`
- Use proper checkbox syntax: `- [ ]` and `- [x]`

### Linking Standards

- Use descriptive link text: `[Schema Architecture](mdc:CLAUDE.md)`
- Reference specific issues/tickets: `Closes #123` or `Related to #456`
- Include Notion page links: `[Project Spec](https://notion.so/...)`

### Content Organization

- Remove irrelevant sections rather than leaving empty
- Keep sections concise but informative
- Use bullet points for lists and structured data
- Include code snippets for complex testing steps

### Prohibited content and footers

- Do not include any footer messages, signatures, boilerplate closings, or meta commentary in PR descriptions. Keep the description limited to the template sections only.
- Examples of prohibited footers: "This standard ensures consistent, high-quality PR descriptions...", "Submitted by <team>", or auto-generated disclaimers.
- When writing content of any section, avoid words like: "to keep consistency and integrity", "to ensure quality", or "to maintain standards". Focus on the specific changes and their impact.

## Quality Gates

### Before Submitting PR

1. **PR title quality** - Clear, descriptive title following title standards
1. **Template completeness** - All relevant sections filled
1. **Content meaningfulness** - No placeholder text remains
1. **Checklist verification** - All items addressed or explained
1. **Link validation** - All references are accessible
1. **Grammar/spelling** - Professional communication standards

### Common Issues to Avoid

- Using conventional commit format in PR titles
- Leaving empty structured prompts
- Generic or vague summaries
- Unchecked checklists without explanation
- Missing testing instructions
- Broken or missing links to related work
- Adding footer messages/signatures/meta commentary at the end of the PR description

